Nov 1 2009 	Comfortable B	My husband and I recently stayed at the Elizabeth Hotel on Eccleston Square for 9 nights. We chose the location for convenience near the Victoria Coach &amp; Tube stations and proximity to Golden Tours starting point. We wanted an affordable and quiet room. Our room was very quiet and clean with a comfortable bed and two pillows apiece. By European standards, I believe our room was very spacious. The carpeting and wall decor were somewhat worn but this did not bother us. There were a lot of stairs, but an elevator as well. The breakfast room was very pleasant, and the continental breakfast was plenty to eat - although full English breakfast was available for a fee. All the staff was very attentive and friendly. There is a also a reception room with tea and newspapers, although I would have liked a separate computer available for customer use.	
Nov 1 2009 	Great Location very clean quiet good value	My husband and I are 60, retired and travel to Europe each year. This was our first trip to London and surrounding areas and we had a wonderful 2+ weeks. We booked the Elizabeth Hotel (in Victoria on Eccleston Square) based on a number of good reviews on Trip Advisor as well as recommendations from a couple of travel books. We were very pleased with our stay at the Elizabeth. First: The location is absolutely terrific. It is very near (just 3 blocks) from Victoria Tube/Train Station and the Victoria Coach station and just about 1/4 mile from Buckingham Palace and there are several great restaurants nearby (see below). Second: The hotel is VERY clean and well maintained. Our room was made-up/serviced every day during our 16 nights. Although some features of the property are a bit &quot;worn&quot; (i.e., carpeting) nevertheless, it is quaint and comfortable. The elevator is small but just fine -- it has some quirks -- for instance: Sometimes you'd get in on the main floor, push your desired floor button, the doors close, you sit there a minute, the door opens and you're still on the main floor -- you wait a minute, the doors close and up you go!) The elevator seems to be &quot;newish&quot; so we think there just might be a programming glitch or something. We just learned to laugh about it and guess if it would be a delay that day or not. We were just thankful for an elevator that worked to take us to our 4th floor room!We had a twin room (2 twin beds) and although it was small, it was just fine. We had a tiny nightstand between the 2 beds, a small &quot;desk&quot; and stool, and small &quot;bureau&quot; with drawers that was handy, plus a small closet and a safe in the closet. We had a great, large window overlooking the street and lovely Eccleston Park across the street. We were pleasantly surprised by how quiet the lovely neighborhood is. Even though you a very close to the train, coach, subway stations/lines, we never heard them! Walking late at night in this neighborhood is very safe, pleasant, and quiet.The only down side about the Elizabeth Hotel was the shower in our en-suite. The hand-held shower head &quot;holder&quot; never worked properly (despite our request that they do something about it). We just learned to wash with one hand and rinse with the other. If they fix the shower head in room 403 it would be great. Bathroom &amp; shower were small but we managed --- it's pretty much expected in London and in other European cities we've visited.The front desk staff is very pleasant and helpful (will provide assistance if you ask them) but they don't provide any unsolicited &quot;tourist-type&quot; information. The kitchent staff is incredibly hospitable, cheery and accommodating. The included buffet breakfast is fantastic (Fresh warm croissants, raisin pastries, warm small french-bread type rolls, white or brown toast made to order, juice, coffee, tea, 3 types of cheeses, 3 types of deli meats, yogurt and several types of cold cereal). You are cheerfully greeted each morning by a lovely staff member, who asks if you would like tea, coffee, juice (orange or grapefruit), and fresh fruit salad. The coffee is french press and delivered fresh and hot to your table. For an extra charge, a full breakfast (eggs, sausage, etc) is also available. On days when we were leaving the hotel early (6am) for a day trip, they will provide you with a &quot;box lunch-type breakfast (cereal with milk, granola bar, etc.)There are several good restaurants within walking distance of the hotel. Several restaurants on Wilton -- just about a 10 minute walk from the hotel, including: &quot;Grad Paradiso&quot; (recommended by the hotel, very good italian food, moderately priced and comfortable, great lamb chops, pastas and salads); &quot;Seafresh&quot; (great seafood, no real ambience to speak of, but the fish was terrific, and we're pretty particular); Kazan (turkish, fantastic lamb shanks and vegetable dishes, the service is great); The &quot;Blue Jade&quot; (Thai food) is just around the corner from the Elizabeth...food is good, it's quiet, and very pleasant after a really hectic day of sightseeing. We also had dinner twice at &quot;Buckingham Balti&quot; (on Buckingham Palace Road near Victoria train sation -- really good curry and chicken tika masala). We ate pizza at Prezzo (very large place, loud, crowded but inexpensive) however, the food was mediocre -- great pizza on Saturday night, terrible Pizza on Tuesday night, pasta both nights was quite bland.All in all we would definitely recommend the Elizabeth Hotel on Eccleston for a budget-minded stay in a great location.	
