Dec 11 2007 	A fair note based on the same price range	I was in London, early Nov, with my husband for our 1st trip to Europe from Singapore. I see very mixed comments abt the Elizabeth and to be fair, I have to say that this hotel is better than some of the other BB in the same areas, at the same price range, rooms and breakfast wise.I also stayed in the Surtees hotel which is nearby and both hotels have their strengths and weaknesses.Elizabeth HotelStrengths: clean room, clean common toilet (if you have opt for a room without an ensuite toilet), nice, warm, hearty English breakfast. We stayed at the top level and the lift goes to the 4th level, the 1 level climb was still manageable for both of us.Weakness: bed is too soft and lumpy, we both ended up with backaches during our stay of 6 days. The problem got better only after we got to Paris where our BB had a much harder bed. My husband has serious back problems, so this is the main reason that we will not return to Elizabeth in the future unless they change their beds.Surtees Hotel:Strengths: at the same price i paid for a double bed room without an ensuite toilet, this place offered the ensuite toilet. Bed was harder than Elizabeth, i.e. not backache inducingWeakness: Stairway was even narrower than the Elizabeth and there is no lift at all in the entire hotel. We were lucky to be on the 2nd level. Breakfast was only toast, fruits and cereals, cold and not satisfying at all. There is also no proper luggage storage area, where we can deposit the luggage after checking out. We were told to just leave them near to the main exit!1 last tip:do NOT travel to London or anywhere in Europe with a heavy luggage. In Singapore and many Asian cities, where we come from, we are pampered with subway/metro stations that has escalators/lifts from the platform all the way to the ground level. But in Europe, where the subways are the oldest in the world, there are only stairs. Having backpacks or manageable trolley bags is the only way to avoid straining yourself.We were very glad to have travelled with 2 small bags and not 1 big one. I feel absolutely sorry for tanie31, but to be fair, I have to say that all BB hotels of this price range are similar in London, so being better prepared is the only way to avoid having such bad experiences. Remember, London is a very old city, buildings like Eceleston Park in Victoria, are more than 100 yrs old, what more can you expect? Also rooms in most London BB are all very small, so small that you hardly have walking space after laying your trolley on the floor- be prepared...	
