Apr 27 2005	A lovely hotel on a beautiful square.	Our family of five just returned from a wonderful three-night stay at the Elizabeth Hotel. We found the hotel clean, well-appointed, and well-maintained, the breakfast ample, well served, and well prepared, and the staff perfectly helpful and competent. Although in a busy, convenient, area, the square itself is quite peaceful and quiet. If you stay at the Elizabeth Hotel, do not miss the opportunity to spend a few relaxing hours in the exquisite square itself. Just ask the receptionist for the key. It is a beautifully maintained botanical garden with room for children to run and play. I would certainly stay at the Elizabeth Hotel again and would recommend it to my friends. Of course getting upgraded from a family room to a 2-bedroom flat for no extra cost certainly contributed to our impression of the place; indeed it convinced me that it would probably be worth paying the extra money for the flat if I ever stayed there again. Besides just enjoyed the additional space, we were able to do laundry there and had a kitchenette, which allowed us to avoid the expense of taking all our meals in restaurants.	
Mar 17 2005 	Booked for the boss	Booking an unknown hotel for someone else (in this case, the Boss) - is always a scary thing to do. On Tuesday 15th March, all my usual City hotels were full. Using the reviews on Trip Advisor and booking through Wotif, I picked the Elizabeth Hotel. Not close to the City, but close to travel links. Its not easy to find a hotel which meets his &quot;good night's sleep&quot; requirements - but this one did.	
Feb 16 2005	Was okay	The Elizabeth Hotel is a quaint hotel. It is in great location next to Victoria Train Station. Our room (triple) was extremely small for 3 people but the room was clean and we had a balcony facing Eccleston Square. The staff was helpful although I don't really think they liked Americans all that much.	
Jan 17 2005	Great Location	Room was small but clean. Bathroom was average size and also clean. Staff was pleasant and breakfast was very good. I'd recommend it.	
Jan 5 2005	good location mediocre hotel	Close to Vitoria Station (walking distance), very quaint street. This is a classic example of you get what you pay for. I wanted something in that area on short notice that was &quot;local&quot;. Found the room on a late rooms web site for under 100gbp. The room was good for sleeping, and that is about it. Bathroom was nothing to get excited about. The help seemed to be mostly young immigrants, not truely hospitality professionals.For one cheap quick night in London it was ok, but I'll take my chances on the many other choices next time.	
Nov 1 2004	Mediocre Start to Finish	I should have known it was a bad sign when they couldn't find my reservation, despite having used the hotel's own web site. Yes, they eventually did give me a room, bouncing some poor (large) family to another hotel -- I wound up in a room for 5, with a view of a ventilation shaft instead of Eccleston Square as I'd been led to believe when making the reservation.The room was basic. The &quot;full English&quot; breakfast was grudging, maybe the least welcoming breakfast I had in 2+ weeks in England. The room was hot (temp couldn't be adjusted). TV was basic, no cable channels.On the plus side: close location to Victoria Station was good, and the neighborhood seemed fine.Overall a disappointment. Not a disaster -- no rats, no break-ins -- but pretty much without charm.	
Oct 12 2004	This is not the London Elizabeth!	My friend and I spent many hours of many days researching London hotels on Trip Advisor. We found a bargain hotel with great reviews: The London Elizabeth Hotel. For months, that was where we thought we were staying for the first two days of our trip in September. That was until we looked at the e-mail confirmation and found out that we had actually booked a room for the Elizabeth Hotel. The reviews for the Elizabeth Hotel weren't nearly as good, but being big believers in fate, we decided to keep our reservation. We had very low expectations, which may have helped, but we were pleased for the most part. The hotel was reasonably close to Victoria Station, but after taking a red eye flight and not sleeping all night, it did seem a bit far to walk (a cab would've been a good idea). The staff ranged from indifferent to snotty, and were fairly useless, but we didn't really need anything while we were there. We had to walk up about 20 flights of stairs to get to our room (no lifts), which wasn't fun. Despite not being air conditioned, the room stayed pretty cool, even when it got to 80 degrees outside (Fahrenheit--obviously). The bathroom was okay: the shower was great, but the wall next to the toilette jutted out at an angle, and my legs were too long to sit normally. So, for the first time in my life, I had to use the toilette sitting sideways. That's one memory I'll always have of the Elizabeth Hotel. Other than that, nothing too memorable--just an okay place to stay.	
Sep 28 2004	good location	We stayed at Elizabeth Hotel in February, 2004. The family room was small for 2 adults and 2 children, but served our purposes. For travellers with heavy luggage it might be inconvenient, though. The bathroom was in good condition. The English breakfast was wonderful and the breakfast room was very clean. The location of the hotel is excellent, especially since we arrived at Victoria Coach Station from Stansted Airport.	
